      <listPerson>
         <person xml:id="person_026">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Henry</forename>
               <surname>Cavendish</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1731"/>
            <death when="1810"/>
            <note>A central figure in English natural philosophy and chemistry, among other research he determined the density of the earth and discovered what would later be named hydrogen. He was one of the people who helped appoint Davy to the Royal Institution. Following his death in 1810 Davy delivered a widely-quoted eulogy on Cavendish and later arranged for some of his apparatus to be transferred to the Royal Institution. FRSL. </note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_030">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Antoine-Laurent</forename>
               <surname>Lavoisier</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1742"/>
            <death when="1794"/>
            <note>French chemist and tax farmer (for which he was guillotined). Developed a new nomenclature for chemistry (much of which is still in use today) and argued strongly against the existence of phlogiston. Davy read some of his writings while in Cornwall which he then opposed and throughout his career maintained an ambivalent attitude towards Lavoisierian chemisty. ForMemRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_321">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">George</forename>
               <surname>Fordyce</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1736"/>
            <death when="1802"/>
            <note>Scottish physician, lecturer on medicine and chemist who worked in London. FRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_144">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Joseph</forename>
               <surname>Banks</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1743ns"/>
            <death when="1820"/>
            <note>A member of the Lincolnshire gentry, Banks sailed as a botanist on James Cook's first voyage to the Pacific (1768-1771). Elected President of the Royal Society of London in 1778 he served for forty-two years until just before his death. The dominant figure in the running of English science during that time, he became one of Davy's patrons and ultimately Davy succeeded him to the Presidency. FRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_142">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Charles</forename>
               <surname>Blagden</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1748"/>
            <death when="1820"/>
            <note>Physician who kept a revealing diary for most of his life. A friend of Joseph Banks serving as a Secretary of the Royal Society of London, 1784-1797; Knighted 1792. FRSL</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_205">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Daniel Carlsson</forename>
               <surname>Solander</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1733"/>
            <death when="1782"/>
            <note>Swedish-born naturalist who worked at the British Museum cataloguing their natural history collections according to the Linnean system. Close to Banks, he accompanied him on various vayages including the Endeavour expedition to the Pacific. FRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_265">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Peter Simon</forename>
               <surname>Pallas</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1741"/>
            <death when="1811"/>
            <note>Prussian explorer, geologist and botanist, who wrote 'Second Voyage de Pallas, ou Voyages entrpris dans les gouvernmens meridionaux de l'empire de Russie, pendant les annees 1793 et 94'</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_016">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Joseph</forename>
               <surname>Priestley</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1733"/>
            <death when="1804"/>
            <note>Unitarian and political radical forced into exile in Pennsylvania. As a natural philospher and chemist who retained belief in phlogiston, he discovered oxygen and nitrous oxide though not under those names. FRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_224">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Carl Wilhelm</forename>
               <surname>Scheele</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1742"/>
            <death when="1786"/>
            <note>Swedish-German pharmaceutical chemist. One of the discoverers of what would later be called oxygen (1771) as well as other chemical elements including what Davy renamed chlorine.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_023">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Richard</forename>
               <surname>Kirwan</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1733"/>
            <death when="1812"/>
            <note>Irish chemist, mineralogist and geologist who accused fellow geologist, James Hutton, of athiesm following publication of his Theory of the Earth (1788). FRSL</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_389">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Pierre Joseph</forename>
               <surname>Macquer</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1718"/>
            <death when="1784"/>
            <note>French chemist who published his Dictionnaire de Chymie in 1766 and later opposed Lavoisier's theories.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_033">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Torbern Olaf</forename>
               <surname>Bergman</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1735"/>
            <death when="1784"/>
            <note>Swedish chemist and mineralogist. At some point Davy acquired a set of letters from Bergman to Franz Schwediaur written in the 1780s which are retained in the Royal Institution (RI MS HD/27/A). ForMemRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_146">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">James</forename>
               <surname>Watt</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1736"/>
            <death when="1819"/>
            <note>A Scottish scientific instrument maker who studied with the chemist Joseph Black at Glasgow University. He developed the separate condenser for steam engines which increased their effieciency significantly. He took out a twenty-five-year patent (ending in 1800) and moved to Birmingham where he went into partnership with the businessman and industrialist Matthew Boulton. They made their fortune by having an effective monopoly of manufacturing steam engines. A friend of Thomas Beddoes, he met Davy on a number of occasions and Davy gave the oration at the unveiling of Watt's statue in Greenock. FRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_927">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">William</forename>
               <surname>Irvine</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1743"/>
            <death when="1787"/>
            <note>FRSE 18th-century British doctor and chemist who served as assistant to Joseph Black in many of his important experiments.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_922">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Adair</forename>
               <surname>Crawford</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1748"/>
            <death when="1795"/>
            <note> A British chemist, physician, and fellow of the Royal Society. He was a pioneer in the development of calorimetric methods for measuring the specific heat capacity of substances and the heat of chemical reactions.</note>
         </person>
      </listPerson>
      <listNym type="chemical">
         <nym xml:id="chemical_012">
            <form>mercury</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: Hg</p>
               <p>Also known as quicksilver. A heavy, silvery element, mercury is the only metallic element that is known to be liquid at standard temperature and pressure.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_417">
            <form>sulphuric acid</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: H2SO3</p>
               <p>A mineral acid composed of the elements sulphur, oxygen, and hydrogen. It is a colourless, odourless, and viscous liquid that is miscible with water.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_030">
            <form>potash</form>
            <def>
               <p>An alkaline substance consisting largely of impure potassium carbonate. In October 1807, Davy decomposed potash using electricity, revealing the previously unknown element potassium.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_014">
            <form>muriate of lime</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: CaCl2</p>
               <p>An inorganic compound and a white crystalline solid at room temperature. Calcium chloride is highly soluble in water, and can be created by neutralising hydrochloric acid with calcium hydroxide.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_187">
            <form>bismuth</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: Bi</p>
               <p>A high-density, silvery, pink-tinged metal.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_046">
            <form>phlogiston</form>
            <def>
               <p>A hypothetical substance, thought of as an elastic fluid, which was believed to exist in combination in all combustible bodies.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_022">
            <form>oxygene</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: O</p>
               <p>Now known as oxygen. Oxygen is a colourless, odourless, tasteless gas essential to living organisms.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_007">
            <form>hydrogene</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: H</p>
               <p>Now known as hydrogen. Hydrogen is the lightest element and, at standard conditions, is a gas of diatomic molecules. It is colourless, odourless, tasteless, non-toxic, and highly combustible.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_336">
            <form>calx</form>
            <def>
               <p>A powdery metallic oxide formed when an ore or mineral has been heated.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_143">
            <form>nitric acid</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: HNO3</p>
               <p>A highly corrosive mineral acid. The compound is colourless, but samples tend to acquire a yellow cast over time due to decomposition into oxides of nitrogen</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
      </listNym>
